recommendations.title: Identify Mystery Pills With This Field Guide
recommendations.excerpt: Ever find a few mystery pills in the bottom of your purse—or worse, in a place your kid or pet may have gotten into? Fortunately every medication has its own distinctive shape, color, and markings, so it’s possible to identify a lost pill.

recommendations.title: Study: Tetris is a great distraction for easing an anxious mind
recommendations.excerpt: There's nothing worse than waiting to hear potentially upsetting news, whether it's a bad medical diagnosis or learning if you got into your top college choice. These kinds of stressful periods can produce intense anxiety.

recommendations.title: San Francisco Tech Billionaires Go to War over Homelessness
recommendations.excerpt: Proposition C, a bill to fight homelessness with a new business tax, slid into San Francisco’s DMs in the middle of the night, politically speaking. What happened was, in December of last year, San Francisco mayor Ed Lee died unexpectedly.

recommendations.title: Wait, Have We Really Wiped Out 60 Percent of Animals?
recommendations.excerpt: Since Monday, news networks and social media has been abuzz with the claim that, as The Guardian among others tweeted, “humanity has wiped out 60 percent of animals since 1970”—a stark and staggering figure based on the latest iteration of the WWF’s Living Planet report.

recommendations.title: Why a Helium Leak Disabled Every iPhone in a Medical Facility
recommendations.excerpt: An IT worker at a medical facility made a remarkable discovery about iPhones and Apple watches earlier this month, after a freshly installed MRI machine appeared to disable every iOS device in the hospital.

recommendations.title: How Everything Became the Culture War
recommendations.excerpt: To understand how American politics got the way it is today, it helps to rewind the tape to the presidential campaign of John McCain—specifically to his effort to win back a listless crowd at an otherwise forgettable campaign event in south-central Pennsylvania in the summer of 2008.

recommendations.title: Steph Curry is the ultimate one-off
recommendations.excerpt: THERE ARE EIGHT players who have won at least three NBA titles and two MVPs. The list reads like the absolute who's who in league history: Kareem. Russell. MJ. Magic. Bird. Duncan. LeBron. Even tangential fans don't need their full names. You shouldn't for the last one on that list, either: Steph.

recommendations.title: Jair Bolsonaro’s Victory Echoes Donald Trump’s, with Key Differences
recommendations.excerpt: On Sunday night, the ultra-rightist candidate Jair Bolsonaro won the second round of Brazil’s Presidential elections.

recommendations.title: Orson Welles and the Birth of Fake News
recommendations.excerpt: Many people believed his famous “War of the Worlds” broadcast — but many didn’t. The difference offers a valuable lesson today. Eighty years ago on Tuesday, Orson Welles revealed the terrifying power of fake news.

recommendations.title: The Case Against Running With Headphones
recommendations.excerpt: In an excerpt from his new book, the NPR host Peter Sagal writes: “If I don’t leave my headphones behind when I run, I wouldn’t spend a single minute of my waking life free from input.”In my long years of running long distances, I have made great use of headphones and iPods.

recommendations.title: Designing peoples’ Instagram Stories is now a million-dollar business
recommendations.excerpt: Every day, 400 million people open up Instagram and flip through Stories, the app’s short, ephemeral photo and video updates from people they follow. Since its launch in 2016, Stories has become a popular way for people to share more about their lives–and more often.

recommendations.title: The Bus Is Still Best
recommendations.excerpt: In some cases, shrinking vehicles is a great idea. Cities don’t have room for everyone’s car. With shared electric scooters, and improvements to bicycle access, people are finding new ways to move without taking up much more space than their body does.

recommendations.title: We Need to Talk More About Mental Health at Work
recommendations.excerpt: Alyssa Mastromonaco is no stranger to tough conversations: she served as White House deputy chief of staff for operations under President Obama, was an executive at Vice and A&E, and is Senior Advisor and spokesperson at NARAL Pro-Choice America.

recommendations.title: Big tech must not reframe digital ethics in its image
recommendations.excerpt: Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg’s visage loomed large over the European parliament this week, both literally and figuratively, as global privacy regulators gathered in Brussels to interrogate the human impacts of technologies that derive their power and persuasiveness from our data.

recommendations.title: The caravan “invasion” and America’s epistemic crisis
recommendations.excerpt: Take a step back and appreciate the vertiginous absurdity of the fact that our military is now being mobilized to defend our border from a walking caravan of refugees from Central America. There are, the Mexican government estimates, around 4,000 people in this group.

recommendations.title: Climate change: Oceans 'soaking up more heat than estimated'
recommendations.excerpt: The world has seriously underestimated the amount of heat soaked up by our oceans over the past 25 years, researchers say. Their study suggests that the seas have absorbed 60% more than previously thought.

recommendations.title: Should you pay off your mortgage early?

recommendations.title: A Hundred Years After the Armistice
recommendations.excerpt: For millions of soldiers, the First World War meant unimaginable horror: artillery shells that could pulverize a human body into a thousand fragments; immense underground mine explosions that could do the same to hundreds of bodies; attacks by poison gas, tanks, flamethrowers.
